Indonesia Stock Movers: Aneka Tambang, Indofood, London Sumatra

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a   a n d   F e m i   A d i
-- 
2011-05-06T09:23:17Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-06/indonesia-stocks-aneka-tambang-london-sumatra-wijaya-karya.html
Shares of the following companies had
unusual moves in Indonesian trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of the 4 p.m. Jakarta-time close.  The  Jakarta Composite index (JCI)  slipped 17.72 points, or 0.5
percent, to 3,798.55. The measure lost 0.6 percent this week.  Metal producers: PT Aneka Tambang (ANTM IJ),  Indonesia ’s
second-biggest nickel producer, fell 1.1 percent to 2,200
rupiah, the lowest close since March 23. PT Timah (TINS IJ), the
nation’s largest tin producer, sank 1.8 percent to 2,750 rupiah,
the biggest decline since April 12.  Nickel futures fell 5 percent to $24,525 a metric ton in
 London  yesterday. Tin lost 6.6 percent to $28,900 a metric ton.  Palm oil producers: PT Astra Agro Lestari (AALI IJ), the
nation’s largest listed plantation company, fell 1.1 percent to
23,400 rupiah. PT Perusahaan Perkebunan London Sumatra Indonesia
(LSIP IJ), the second-biggest, lost 2 percent to 2,425 rupiah,  Palm oil futures fell for a third day, losing as much as
2.5 percent to 3,148 ringgit ($1,047) a metric ton in  Kuala
Lumpur  today.  PT Indofood Sukses Makmur (INDF IJ), which owns Indonesia’s
biggest instant noodle maker, rose 1.8 percent to 5,700 rupiah,
the highest close since Sept. 22. The company’s unit, PT Salim
Ivomas Pratama, plans to sell 3.16 billion new shares at 200
rupiah each in an initial share sale next month, the unit said
in a statement published in  Bisnis Indonesia  today. The proceeds
will be used to build processing facilities, pay bank loans, and
buy transport vessels, it said.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at   dboey@bloomberg.net  